all types of crimes.

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:30.890
Been married to my one and
only wife for 40-plus years.

00:01:30.890 --> 00:01:32.826
Three sons, five grandchildren.

00:01:32.826 --> 00:01:34.828
A son who's an FBI agent.

00:01:34.828 --> 00:01:37.230 align:start size:84% position:16%
A kind of amazing
other side of my life

00:01:37.230 --> 00:01:39.165
than the side people
know from the movie.

00:01:39.165 --> 00:01:41.701 align:start size:88% position:13%
- [Doug] Well those
five years from 16 to 21

00:01:41.701 --> 00:01:44.571 align:start size:94% position:6%
were filled with some very
interesting adventures.

00:01:44.571 --> 00:01:48.341 align:start size:97% position:3%
You impersonated an
airline pilot, a physician,

00:01:48.341 --> 00:01:51.077 align:start size:84% position:16%
an attorney, and a
federal prisons agent.

00:01:51.077 --> 00:01:53.246 align:start size:84% position:16%
So let's talk about
the pilot one,

00:01:53.246 --> 00:01:56.416
just to set the scene for how
you did this kind of thing.

00:01:56.416 --> 00:01:58.184
- Well you know,
people always say

00:01:58.184 --> 00:02:00.920
that they thought I was
brilliant when in fact

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:04.357
I was just an adolescent, so
I had no fear of being caught.

00:02:04.357 --> 00:02:06.459
I never premeditated anything.

00:02:06.459 --> 00:02:10.096
I had ran away from home
at 16, back in the '60s

00:02:10.096 --> 00:02:12.298
a lot of kids ran away from
home but they got caught up

00:02:12.298 --> 00:02:15.135 align:start size:97% position:3%
in Haight-Ashbury, the
hippie scene, the drug scene.

00:02:15.135 --> 00:02:16.870
I ended up on the
streets in New York

00:02:16.870 --> 00:02:19.539
and didn't have any money,
I kind of quickly realized

00:02:19.539 --> 00:02:22.208 align:start size:84% position:16%
that as long as people
believed I was 16

00:02:22.208 --> 00:02:23.710
I wasn't going to get anywhere.

00:02:23.710 --> 00:02:25.979
So the first thing I did was
alter my driver's license.

00:02:25.979 --> 00:02:28.448
Back then didn't
have a photo on it.

00:02:28.448 --> 00:02:30.583
It was just an IBM card
so I altered one digit

00:02:30.583 --> 00:02:32.118
of my date of birth.

00:02:32.118 --> 00:02:35.522
I was actually born in April
of 1948, I dropped the four,

00:02:35.522 --> 00:02:37.323
converted it to it three.

00:02:37.323 --> 00:02:39.792
So that made me 26 years old.

00:02:39.792 --> 00:02:42.262
And I started writing checks.

00:02:42.262 --> 00:02:43.930 align:start size:84% position:16%
I had an account,
when the money ran out

00:02:43.930 --> 00:02:46.799 align:start size:94% position:6%
I kept writing the
checks to support myself.

00:02:46.799 --> 00:02:49.802 align:start size:88% position:13%
And one day I was
walking down the street

00:02:49.802 --> 00:02:52.472 align:start size:94% position:6%
and I saw an airline
crew come out of a hotel,

00:02:52.472 --> 00:02:56.075
and I thought to myself if
I could get that uniform,

00:02:56.075 --> 00:02:58.144
then when I walked into a bank

00:02:58.144 --> 00:02:59.179 align:start size:84% position:16%
it would give so
much more credibility

00:02:59.179 --> 00:03:00.914
to asking to cash a check.

00:03:00.914 --> 00:03:04.717
And that was the sole purpose
of it, nothing more than that.

00:03:04.717 --> 00:03:07.587 align:start size:88% position:13%
So I was able to finagle
getting a uniform,

00:03:07.587 --> 00:03:09.989 align:start size:81% position:19%
once I got the
uniform I realized

00:03:09.989 --> 00:03:12.025 align:start size:84% position:16%
that you could
actually board planes

00:03:12.025 --> 00:03:15.094
and ride on planes for
free in the jump seat.

00:03:15.094 --> 00:03:17.797
So I did that and I was
able to stay in hotels

00:03:17.797 --> 00:03:19.832 align:start size:84% position:16%
and bill the
airline for my room.

00:03:19.832 --> 00:03:23.770 align:start size:84% position:16%
So by the two
years from 16 to 18

00:03:23.770 --> 00:03:25.638
I flew in more than 260 aircraft

00:03:25.638 --> 00:03:28.608 align:start size:94% position:6%
in more than 62 countries
around the world.

00:03:28.608 --> 00:03:31.644
Just riding the jump seat
and posing as a pilot.

00:03:31.644 --> 00:03:34.280
But it started out as more
of a front for the checks

00:03:34.280 --> 00:03:36.549 align:start size:81% position:19%
and then every
time I moved along

00:03:36.549 --> 00:03:38.351
something else would come up

00:03:38.351 --> 00:03:39.786
and I was somewhat
of an opportunist,

00:03:39.786 --> 00:03:41.654 align:start size:97% position:3%
so I saw it as an
opportunity and I took that

00:03:41.654 --> 00:03:42.889
to the next step.

00:03:42.889 --> 00:03:45.191 line:0%
- [Mill] Was there a
thrill in it for you?

00:03:45.191 --> 00:03:46.926 line:0%
- Not so much the thrill
as a more of a survival

00:03:46.926 --> 00:03:50.530 line:0%
and running from the law
and how to avoid the law.

00:03:50.530 --> 00:03:52.632
I could travel around the
world without a passport

00:03:52.632 --> 00:03:54.934
on an airline crew card.

00:03:54.934 --> 00:03:58.438
There were a lot of reasons
I did it other than just,

00:03:58.438 --> 00:04:00.506
I don't think there was
ever really a thrill,

00:04:00.506 --> 00:04:02.842 align:start size:97% position:3%
it was more about just staying
one step ahead of the law

00:04:02.842 --> 00:04:06.079
and staying one step
of trying to survive.

00:04:06.079 --> 00:04:08.381
- Were you ever in the cockpit?

00:04:08.381 --> 00:04:11.284
- Many many times, most of
the time in the cockpit,

00:04:11.284 --> 00:04:12.819
but in the jump seat.

00:04:12.819 --> 00:04:15.421 align:start size:88% position:13%
I was smart enough
never to ride on Pan Am,

00:04:15.421 --> 00:04:17.724
which was the pilot
I was posing as,

00:04:17.724 --> 00:04:19.192
because I was always afraid

00:04:19.192 --> 00:04:21.861
someone would start asking
me questions about who I knew

00:04:21.861 --> 00:04:23.696
and where I was based.

00:04:23.696 --> 00:04:25.598
So I always rode
on other carriers.

00:04:25.598 --> 00:04:27.634
And then I also knew
they would never ask me

00:04:27.634 --> 00:04:29.402 align:start size:81% position:19%
to do any function
in the cockpit,

00:04:29.402 --> 00:04:33.172
since I was a pilot riding the
jump seat on another carrier.

00:04:33.172 --> 00:04:35.108 align:start size:84% position:16%
So I always put
those things in place

00:04:35.108 --> 00:04:37.176
so that I didn't get
myself in a situation

00:04:37.176 --> 00:04:38.511
I couldn't get out of.

00:04:38.511 --> 00:04:40.647 align:start position:0%
- [Doug] Well, you impersonated
a physician as well,

00:04:40.647 --> 00:04:43.850 align:start size:97% position:3%
so how did you protect
other people from yourself?

00:04:43.850 --> 00:04:46.686 align:start size:88% position:13%
- Again, the same thing,
I moved to Atlanta,

00:04:46.686 --> 00:04:48.821
and I moved into an
apartment complex.

00:04:48.821 --> 00:04:50.757
On the application
it asked profession,

00:04:50.757 --> 00:04:53.459
so I didn't want to
put airline pilot

00:04:53.459 --> 00:04:54.861
because the police
were looking for me,

00:04:54.861 --> 00:04:57.530
so I put down doctor
and left it at that.

00:04:57.530 --> 00:04:59.532 align:start size:84% position:16%
Had a very inquisitive
apartment manager

00:04:59.532 --> 00:05:01.167 align:start size:84% position:16%
who asked me what
kind of doctor I was,

00:05:01.167 --> 00:05:05.071 align:start size:97% position:3%
so I said pediatrician because
it was a singles complex

00:05:05.071 --> 00:05:06.773
and there were no
children there.

00:05:06.773 --> 00:05:09.909
And then the next thing you
know I met a pediatrician

00:05:09.909 --> 00:05:11.377
who lived there.

00:05:11.377 --> 00:05:13.479 align:start size:94% position:6%
I got to know him he took
me up to the hospital

00:05:13.479 --> 00:05:14.781
to meet people.

00:05:14.781 --> 00:05:17.350 align:start size:88% position:13%
And then one day he
asked me if I would mind

00:05:17.350 --> 00:05:19.852
covering a shift at the
hospital for two weeks

00:05:19.852 --> 00:05:22.789
while a doctor had gone
home because of a death,

00:05:22.789 --> 00:05:25.091 align:start size:88% position:13%
and that it was an
administrative position,

00:05:25.091 --> 00:05:26.893
didn't have to treat anybody.

00:05:26.893 --> 00:05:29.162
And so again I saw it
more as a challenge

00:05:29.162 --> 00:05:30.697
to see if I could get
away with doing it,

00:05:30.697 --> 00:05:34.000
so I went to the hospital
and worked in the hospital.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.370 align:start position:0%
In the hospital and the lawyer,
no one really ever doubted

00:05:37.370 --> 00:05:40.106
I was not that person, it
was I who left on my own.

00:05:40.106 --> 00:05:41.674
- [Doug] Nobody said,
here's an emergency,

00:05:41.674 --> 00:05:43.209
it's time for you to--

00:05:43.209 --> 00:05:45.011
- No, because it was mainly
an administrative position,

00:05:45.011 --> 00:05:48.314 align:start position:0%
so I kind of just administrated
the staff on my shift,

00:05:48.314 --> 00:05:50.383 align:start size:84% position:16%
so it wasn't a very
difficult thing to do.

00:05:50.383 --> 00:05:52.518
- [Doug] Well, you were
ultimately apprehended

00:05:52.518 --> 00:05:54.320
at a pretty tender age, 21.

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:55.722 align:start size:72% position:28%
- Yes.
- In Europe.

00:05:55.722 --> 00:05:58.291
- I was arrested by
the French police

00:05:58.291 --> 00:05:59.692
when I was 21 years old,

00:05:59.692 --> 00:06:02.195 align:start position:0%
actually on an Interpol
warrant from the Swedish police

00:06:02.195 --> 00:06:05.098
who were looking for me
for forgery in Sweden,

00:06:05.098 --> 00:06:07.567
but they believed I
was living in France.

00:06:07.567 --> 00:06:09.635 align:start position:0%
But when the French authorities
took me into custody

00:06:09.635 --> 00:06:12.505
on the Swedish warrant they
realized I had forged checks

00:06:12.505 --> 00:06:15.475 align:start size:97% position:3%
all over France, so they
refused to honor the warrant

00:06:15.475 --> 00:06:17.610 align:start size:81% position:19%
and they requested
my extradition.

00:06:17.610 --> 00:06:19.545 align:start size:88% position:13%
And they later
convicted me of forgery

00:06:19.545 --> 00:06:21.547
and sent me to French prison.

00:06:21.547 --> 00:06:23.516
I eventually served
my time in France,

00:06:23.516 --> 00:06:25.084
was extradited to Sweden,

00:06:25.084 --> 00:06:27.253
where I served time in
a Swedish penitentiary

00:06:27.253 --> 00:06:29.021
in Malmo, Sweden.

00:06:29.021 --> 00:06:31.190
When my sentence was up,
US federal authorities

00:06:31.190 --> 00:06:33.659 align:start size:97% position:3%
took custody of me, returned
me to the United States,

00:06:33.659 --> 00:06:35.995
and eventually a United
States federal judge

00:06:35.995 --> 00:06:38.164
in Atlanta Georgia sentenced me

00:06:38.164 --> 00:06:41.334
to 12 years in federal prison.

00:06:41.334 --> 00:06:43.669 align:start size:88% position:13%
I served about four
years of those 12 years

00:06:43.669 --> 00:06:46.639
at a federal prison in
Petersburg, Virginia.

00:06:46.639 --> 00:06:49.008
When I was 26 years old
the government offered to

00:06:49.008 --> 00:06:50.977 align:start size:84% position:16%
take me out of prison
on the condition

00:06:50.977 --> 00:06:53.713 align:start size:97% position:3%
I'd go to work with an agency
of the federal government

00:06:53.713 --> 00:06:55.047
for the remainder of my sentence

00:06:55.047 --> 00:06:58.017
or until my parole
had been completed.

00:06:58.017 --> 00:07:02.889
I agreed and I've spent the
last four decades at the FBI.

00:07:02.889 --> 00:07:05.958 align:start size:88% position:13%
- So you're put in
prison at the age of 21.

00:07:05.958 --> 00:07:09.662
And ultimately you come out
of prison helping the FBI

00:07:09.662 --> 00:07:11.531
and the federal government.

00:07:11.531 --> 00:07:13.399
How did that happen?

00:07:13.399 --> 00:07:16.736 line:0%
- Two reasons, at the time,
this was right after Hoover,

00:07:16.736 --> 00:07:19.071 line:0%
Clarence Kelly was the
director of the Bureau.

00:07:20.273 --> 00:07:22.542
I think one, to teach
agents at the academy

00:07:22.542 --> 00:07:25.611 align:start size:84% position:16%
where I've taught
for four decades now.

00:07:25.611 --> 00:07:27.213
I had to go out in the
field and teach agents

00:07:27.213 --> 00:07:28.948
how to think out of the box,

00:07:28.948 --> 00:07:31.884
how to look at things not
just as black and white,

00:07:31.884 --> 00:07:33.686
how to deal with
social engineering,

00:07:33.686 --> 00:07:36.189 align:start size:84% position:16%
so that they can use
it in a legal way

00:07:36.189 --> 00:07:37.657
to gather information.

00:07:37.657 --> 00:07:40.960 align:start size:84% position:16%
And also in the first
part of my career

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:42.695
I did a lot of undercover work,

00:07:42.695 --> 00:07:45.097 align:start size:84% position:16%
mainly because the
bureau could say to me

00:07:45.097 --> 00:07:47.266
I need you to be this
particular person,

00:07:47.266 --> 00:07:48.935
a lieutenant in the Army.

00:07:48.935 --> 00:07:52.004 align:start size:84% position:16%
Your expertise is this
particular missile.

00:07:52.004 --> 00:07:53.606 align:start size:81% position:19%
I need you to know
enough about it

00:07:53.606 --> 00:07:56.075
to go onto this base and
find out what's going on

00:07:56.075 --> 00:07:58.277
about whatever it
might be the event.

00:07:58.277 --> 00:08:01.380
So I think a lot of it was
all of those things combined.

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:03.950
I don't think they ever
dreamed or I ever dreamed

00:08:03.950 --> 00:08:07.987
I would stay there more than
the allotted time of my parole,

00:08:07.987 --> 00:08:12.325 align:start size:97% position:3%
but when my parole was up
and the court order was over,

00:08:12.325 --> 00:08:14.627
they asked me to
stay and I stayed

00:08:14.627 --> 00:08:15.828
and have been there ever since.

00:08:15.828 --> 00:08:17.563
- In the course of your
doing time in prison

00:08:17.563 --> 00:08:20.633
and subsequently working
with the federal government

00:08:20.633 --> 00:08:24.670
on various security
issues have you ever,

00:08:24.670 --> 00:08:26.172
over the course of your life,

00:08:26.172 --> 00:08:30.810 align:start size:97% position:3%
had the occasion to sort of
look inwardly and ask yourself

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:32.612
why did I do this?

00:08:32.612 --> 00:08:35.715 align:start size:94% position:6%
- I think it was just
more about being a runaway

00:08:35.715 --> 00:08:38.084 align:start size:84% position:16%
and then thinking
about how to survive,

00:08:38.084 --> 00:08:40.119
and those kind of things.

00:08:40.119 --> 00:08:42.688
I think it was more about that
there was no real motivation

00:08:42.688 --> 00:08:45.458
to want to be a pilot, be
a doctor, or be a lawyer.

00:08:45.458 --> 00:08:47.627
All of those things I
fell into, the lawyer,

00:08:47.627 --> 00:08:51.030
I met a girl whose father
was the Attorney General

00:08:51.030 --> 00:08:54.600
in Louisiana and I
ended up telling her

00:08:54.600 --> 00:08:57.103
I had a law degree.

00:08:57.103 --> 00:09:00.039
As I went to Louisiana
I actually took the bar,

00:09:00.039 --> 00:09:03.743 align:start position:0%
I passed the bar, so I
practiced law there for a while.

00:09:03.743 --> 00:09:06.812
I think it was all a matter
of just going on knowing

00:09:06.812 --> 00:09:08.614
that sooner or later
I would get caught.

00:09:08.614 --> 00:09:12.385
I always knew I'd get caught,
it was just a matter of time.

00:09:12.385 --> 00:09:15.221 align:start position:0%
But it was just a matter of
how long I could stretch it out

00:09:15.221 --> 00:09:17.323
and how long I could
just keep going along

00:09:17.323 --> 00:09:18.824
and just encountered things.

00:09:19.959 --> 00:09:21.661 align:start size:84% position:16%
And again very much
an opportunist,

00:09:21.661 --> 00:09:23.796
very much an adolescent who
had no fear of being caught.

00:09:23.796 --> 00:09:26.165
Didn't think of
the consequences.

00:09:26.165 --> 00:09:27.867
Didn't premeditate anything,

00:09:27.867 --> 00:09:29.535
if I was standing out
in front of a bank

00:09:29.535 --> 00:09:32.705
with a check for $500,
I didn't have a plan,

00:09:32.705 --> 00:09:35.708
I didn't say I was going to
go in and if they say this

00:09:35.708 --> 00:09:38.311
I'll do this if they
do that I'll do that.

00:09:38.311 --> 00:09:39.879 align:start size:81% position:19%
I just simply went
in and did it,

00:09:39.879 --> 00:09:41.814
so everything was kind
of ad-libbed and I think

00:09:41.814 --> 00:09:43.783 align:start size:81% position:19%
that was very much
the adolescent.

00:09:43.783 --> 00:09:47.086 align:start size:97% position:3%
But I think the adolescent was
why I was successful at it.

00:09:47.086 --> 00:09:49.989 align:start size:88% position:13%
Had I been a little
smarter, a little older,

00:09:49.989 --> 00:09:52.158
I think I would have
started to rationalize

00:09:52.158 --> 00:09:54.727
and say you'll never get away
with that, you can't do that,

00:09:54.727 --> 00:09:56.762 align:start size:81% position:19%
and I probably
wouldn't have done

00:09:56.762 --> 00:09:58.030
half the things that I did.

00:09:58.030 --> 00:09:59.732
- [Doug] Well it sounds
like you were following

00:09:59.732 --> 00:10:03.035 align:start size:97% position:3%
the KISS principle, the keep
it simple principle here,

00:10:03.035 --> 00:10:05.705
in terms of hoodwinking people.

