in fraudulent claims

00:15:00.199 --> 00:15:03.168 align:start position:0%
to criminals who lived in other
countries around the world.

00:15:03.168 --> 00:15:07.339
$200 billion, that's 10%
of Medicare and Medicaid's

00:15:07.339 --> 00:15:10.175
annual budget went to criminals.

00:15:10.175 --> 00:15:13.345 align:start size:84% position:16%
So the government does
a very horrible job

00:15:13.345 --> 00:15:15.281
of protecting information.

00:15:15.281 --> 00:15:17.917 align:start size:94% position:6%
So I would say that you're
in much better hands,

00:15:17.917 --> 00:15:19.418
it's not anything foolproof,

00:15:19.418 --> 00:15:20.986
but you're much better
hands with your bank

00:15:20.986 --> 00:15:22.821 align:start size:84% position:16%
than you would be
with the government.

00:15:22.821 --> 00:15:26.258 align:start size:97% position:3%
- There are lots of scams
that involve senior citizens,

00:15:26.258 --> 00:15:28.093
and they evolve over time,

00:15:28.093 --> 00:15:31.230
but maybe you could share with
our viewers some of the scams

00:15:31.230 --> 00:15:34.099
that are current and
what they should do.

00:15:34.099 --> 00:15:36.168
- I use very simple
rules, so for example

00:15:36.168 --> 00:15:38.137
the most common scams
we have right now,

00:15:38.137 --> 00:15:40.306
one is called the
grandparent scam.

00:15:40.306 --> 00:15:43.375
So the telephone rings, you
walk over to the caller ID,

00:15:43.375 --> 00:15:45.878 align:start size:88% position:13%
and it says it's the
Fargo Police Department.

00:15:45.878 --> 00:15:48.013
So you pick it up
because you believe

00:15:48.013 --> 00:15:49.515 align:start size:81% position:19%
it is the Fargo
Police Department.

00:15:49.515 --> 00:15:52.851
One of the simplest things
to manipulate is caller ID.

00:15:52.851 --> 00:15:54.987 align:start size:94% position:6%
Someone says that they're
Sergeant So-and-So

00:15:54.987 --> 00:15:56.455 align:start size:81% position:19%
with the Fargo
Police Department,

00:15:56.455 --> 00:16:00.359 align:start size:97% position:3%
they've arrested your grandson
for DWI on Interstate 94.

00:16:00.359 --> 00:16:02.561
And they describe
his car to you,

00:16:02.561 --> 00:16:04.630 align:start size:84% position:16%
they describe the
name of his girlfriend

00:16:04.630 --> 00:16:06.665
that was riding in
the car with him.

00:16:06.665 --> 00:16:09.601 align:start position:0%
All the details, and then
simply tell you that he asked us

00:16:09.601 --> 00:16:12.071
not to call his parents,
he asked us to call you.

00:16:12.071 --> 00:16:13.872
He'll have to spend
the weekend in jail

00:16:13.872 --> 00:16:16.008 align:start size:84% position:16%
before he sees a judge
unless he post bail

00:16:16.008 --> 00:16:17.543
in the next couple of hours.

00:16:17.543 --> 00:16:20.145 align:start size:97% position:3%
Of course the grandparent
says, oh how much is the bail,

00:16:20.145 --> 00:16:23.182
you know, $500, and you can
give us a credit card number

00:16:23.182 --> 00:16:24.917
and we can release him.

00:16:24.917 --> 00:16:28.053
And it's amazing how
many, unfortunately
millions of people,

00:16:28.053 --> 00:16:29.588
fall for that every day.

00:16:29.588 --> 00:16:31.623
So if you explain
that to anyone,

00:16:31.623 --> 00:16:33.225 align:start size:88% position:13%
whether they are a
senior or a millennial,

00:16:33.225 --> 00:16:35.294
and you tell them
how the scam works,

00:16:35.294 --> 00:16:38.430
the next time that call comes
and that information comes

00:16:38.430 --> 00:16:41.734
about your grandson or
someone's in custody,

00:16:41.734 --> 00:16:44.703
they know smart enough
to hang up the phone,

00:16:44.703 --> 00:16:47.373
pick up the phone book, look
up the Fargo Police Department

00:16:47.373 --> 00:16:49.908
in the phone book, call
the police department,

00:16:49.908 --> 00:16:51.643 align:start size:84% position:16%
and ask them if they
placed that call.

00:16:51.643 --> 00:16:54.113 align:start size:84% position:16%
That takes two
minutes to do that.

00:16:54.113 --> 00:16:57.683 align:start size:84% position:16%
So I'm a big believer
in stop, verify.

00:16:57.683 --> 00:17:01.820
If you get a phone call from
the IRS and you're concerned

00:17:01.820 --> 00:17:04.656
that it is a real call, the IRS
really doesn't call anybody,

00:17:04.656 --> 00:17:07.359
but if you do get a
call from the IRS,

00:17:07.359 --> 00:17:08.827
then just simply
hang up the phone,

00:17:08.827 --> 00:17:10.129
again go to the phone book,

00:17:10.129 --> 00:17:12.364
don't call the number
back they gave you.

00:17:12.364 --> 00:17:15.167
Look up the IRS, call the
IRS, tell them you received

00:17:15.167 --> 00:17:18.237
that phone call, and of
course they'll tell you

00:17:18.237 --> 00:17:20.305 align:start size:88% position:13%
that that's a fictitious
fraudulent call.

00:17:20.305 --> 00:17:23.709
So it doesn't take but a
minute to stop and verify,

00:17:23.709 --> 00:17:26.045
and that's what I tell
people is the solution

00:17:26.045 --> 00:17:28.847
to most all of these scams.

00:17:28.847 --> 00:17:30.783 align:start size:84% position:16%
- [Doug] Well, a
common scam years ago,

00:17:30.783 --> 00:17:33.218 align:start size:94% position:6%
and it keeps coming
around in some variation,

00:17:33.218 --> 00:17:35.988
is the Nigerian windfall.

00:17:35.988 --> 00:17:37.956 align:start size:81% position:19%
The email that
comes to me saying

00:17:37.956 --> 00:17:40.592
there's all this money
that might come my way

00:17:40.592 --> 00:17:42.194
with a modest investment.

00:17:42.194 --> 00:17:43.862 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
- Yeah, and they've
moved along from that,

00:17:43.862 --> 00:17:46.799 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
you know the Nigerians years
ago people used to ask me

00:17:46.799 --> 00:17:50.002
how they sent out thousands
and thousands of letters,

00:17:50.002 --> 00:17:52.371 align:start size:84% position:16%
who paid the postage
for the stamps.

00:17:52.371 --> 00:17:55.240 align:start size:97% position:3%
And I told them that the
stamps were all counterfeit.

00:17:55.240 --> 00:17:59.144 align:start position:0%
So they paid nothing for
fraudulent stamps from Nigeria.

00:17:59.144 --> 00:18:00.712 align:start size:84% position:16%
The difference
today with that scam

00:18:00.712 --> 00:18:03.248
is you used to send
out 10,000 letters

00:18:03.248 --> 00:18:06.452
and hope that 1/10th
of 1% would respond.

00:18:06.452 --> 00:18:08.654 align:start size:97% position:3%
Today, through the
Internet, you could send out

00:18:08.654 --> 00:18:11.723 align:start size:88% position:13%
10 million letters,
and again you only need

00:18:11.723 --> 00:18:14.193
1/10th of 1% to respond.

00:18:14.193 --> 00:18:17.863 align:start size:84% position:16%
So it's basically
the same scam again.

00:18:17.863 --> 00:18:20.699
And all these scams,

00:18:20.699 --> 00:18:23.669 align:start size:88% position:13%
as I tell people, the
same way in a love scam,

00:18:23.669 --> 00:18:26.538
someone might have met
someone on the Internet,

00:18:26.538 --> 00:18:29.007
they've been involved for
six months talking to them

00:18:29.007 --> 00:18:30.442
back and forth on the Internet,

00:18:30.442 --> 00:18:32.077
they've spoken to
them on the phone.

00:18:32.077 --> 00:18:33.879
They never met them personally,

00:18:33.879 --> 00:18:36.582
they tell them they live in the
next state over in Minnesota

00:18:36.582 --> 00:18:38.050
or wherever they might be.

00:18:38.050 --> 00:18:40.853
And one day out of the
clear blue they say well,

00:18:40.853 --> 00:18:44.389
I'd come and see you but I
have to have an operation.

00:18:44.389 --> 00:18:45.858
I don't have the money for it

00:18:45.858 --> 00:18:48.393 align:start size:97% position:3%
and if I don't have the
operation I might, you know,

00:18:48.393 --> 00:18:49.828
might lose my life.

00:18:49.828 --> 00:18:53.132 align:start size:97% position:3%
Oh well, how much is the
operation, well it's $35,000.

00:18:53.132 --> 00:18:54.433
Well I'll give you the money.

00:18:54.433 --> 00:18:56.702
So the minute someone
asks you for money

00:18:56.702 --> 00:18:58.937 align:start size:84% position:16%
or someone asked
you for information,

00:18:58.937 --> 00:19:00.439 align:start size:84% position:16%
social security
number, date of birth,

00:19:00.439 --> 00:19:01.840
bank account information,

00:19:01.840 --> 00:19:04.042
that's when the red
flag should go up.

00:19:04.042 --> 00:19:07.312 align:start size:88% position:13%
So there are obvious
red flags in every scam.

00:19:07.312 --> 00:19:09.615
And if you learn to
spot those red flags

00:19:09.615 --> 00:19:12.217
that's when you need to
end that relationship

00:19:12.217 --> 00:19:14.353
end that conversation and know

00:19:14.353 --> 00:19:16.555
that there's actually a scam
being perpetrated against you.

00:19:16.555 --> 00:19:19.358
- [Doug] There's a sort of an
emotional involvement here,

00:19:19.358 --> 00:19:20.792
too though, some of these scams,

00:19:20.792 --> 00:19:22.895
and even the ones you
talked about yourself,

00:19:22.895 --> 00:19:25.864 align:start size:88% position:13%
becoming an attorney
because your girlfriend,

00:19:25.864 --> 00:19:28.333 align:start size:84% position:16%
there was some sort
of a connection there.

00:19:28.333 --> 00:19:32.070
How good are fraud
artists, con men,

00:19:32.070 --> 00:19:33.672
at sort of reading people?

00:19:35.107 --> 00:19:36.875
- They're very good and people,

00:19:38.277 --> 00:19:40.412 align:start position:0%
you know I have two incidences,
my neighbor next to me,

00:19:40.412 --> 00:19:42.681
