00:30:33.832 --> 00:30:36.034
which is in Columbus Ohio.

00:30:36.034 --> 00:30:39.304 align:start size:97% position:3%
Now they have 15,000 people
at Nationwide on their campus,

00:30:39.304 --> 00:30:41.573
so when I go there I
have to spend a day,

00:30:41.573 --> 00:30:43.474 align:start size:94% position:6%
I have to go to the
auditorium, the cafeteria,

00:30:43.474 --> 00:30:45.543
keep speaking to people.

00:30:45.543 --> 00:30:49.581
My message to them is that the
most important job they have,

00:30:49.581 --> 00:30:52.016
whether they're the
janitor or the CEO,

00:30:52.016 --> 00:30:54.953
is to protect the information
that's been entrusted to them

00:30:54.953 --> 00:30:56.387
by their clients.

00:30:56.387 --> 00:30:57.922
So when I get out
to those companies

00:30:57.922 --> 00:30:59.224
I have a little thing I do,

00:30:59.224 --> 00:31:01.025
I don't park in the
visitor parking lot.

00:31:01.025 --> 00:31:03.228 align:start size:84% position:16%
I park in the
employee parking lot.

00:31:03.228 --> 00:31:05.129
When I get out of the
car empty my pockets

00:31:05.129 --> 00:31:08.032
of some memory sticks
that say confidential.

00:31:08.032 --> 00:31:10.034 align:start size:84% position:16%
And I throw them all
over the grounds.

00:31:10.034 --> 00:31:12.403
I have a tracing device
on them so at lunch time

00:31:12.403 --> 00:31:14.973
in the cafeteria I open it
up to see how many employees

00:31:14.973 --> 00:31:16.341
went to see what it said.

00:31:16.341 --> 00:31:19.878
And it says, "This is
a test and you failed."

00:31:19.878 --> 00:31:22.480
But in five years, at
hundreds of companies,

00:31:22.480 --> 00:31:24.916
I have yet to have
that not happen.

00:31:24.916 --> 00:31:26.551
Someone's gonna go look.

00:31:26.551 --> 00:31:29.254
Later I explain to them that I
could have cost their company

00:31:29.254 --> 00:31:31.189
a billion dollars overnight

00:31:31.189 --> 00:31:33.691
and destroyed their
100-year old brand.

00:31:33.691 --> 00:31:35.660
So there is nothing
more important again

00:31:35.660 --> 00:31:38.263 align:start size:84% position:16%
than educating
employees in a company

00:31:38.263 --> 00:31:40.398
about protecting the
information and data

00:31:40.398 --> 00:31:44.969
that's been entrusted to
them by their their clients

00:31:44.969 --> 00:31:46.871
or their citizens or
whoever it may be.

00:31:46.871 --> 00:31:48.573 align:start size:88% position:13%
- [Doug] So just picking
up that memory stick,

00:31:48.573 --> 00:31:50.341
putting it in your
company computer,

00:31:50.341 --> 00:31:51.743
unloads maybe a program--

00:31:51.743 --> 00:31:53.511
- Right, that's it.

00:31:53.511 --> 00:31:54.746
Going to a link that came up

00:31:54.746 --> 00:31:55.713
because a friend
sent you something,

00:31:55.713 --> 00:31:57.382
you believe it's your friend.

00:31:57.382 --> 00:32:00.018
There are so many
of those things,

00:32:00.018 --> 00:32:03.087 align:start size:84% position:16%
99% of malware
comes from phishing.

00:32:03.087 --> 00:32:05.456
So they're all by emails
or somebody telling you

00:32:05.456 --> 00:32:08.226
to do something that you're
probably not supposed to do.

00:32:08.226 --> 00:32:11.296 align:start size:94% position:6%
- [Doug] Equifax of course
went on the offensive,

00:32:11.296 --> 00:32:15.366 align:start size:97% position:3%
in terms of its PR
protection, to let people know

00:32:15.366 --> 00:32:17.602 align:start size:81% position:19%
that they were
going to help them

00:32:17.602 --> 00:32:19.237 align:start size:84% position:16%
determine the depth
of the problem

00:32:19.237 --> 00:32:21.339
they might personally have.

00:32:21.339 --> 00:32:24.008
In my case there was going
to be a deep Internet search

00:32:24.008 --> 00:32:25.977
of whether or not my
social security number,

00:32:25.977 --> 00:32:29.113
my phone number, some other
data, of my email address,

00:32:29.113 --> 00:32:30.848
was broadly available.

00:32:30.848 --> 00:32:35.353 align:start size:97% position:3%
I came up clean but somehow
I don't feel secure.

00:32:35.353 --> 00:32:38.756 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
- I kind of felt that
the whole Equifax thing,

00:32:38.756 --> 00:32:42.493 line:0%
what they did post-breach
was a little bit unethical.

00:32:42.493 --> 00:32:45.930 align:start size:97% position:3%
So first of all they
immediately came out and said

00:32:45.930 --> 00:32:49.400
that they will provide one year
of credit monitoring service

00:32:49.400 --> 00:32:53.571
for free, so millions of
people went and signed up

00:32:53.571 --> 00:32:56.274
for Equifax credit
monitoring service.

00:32:56.274 --> 00:32:58.977
Then as the year passed
they came back and said,

00:32:58.977 --> 00:33:01.913 align:start size:94% position:6%
well nothing's really
came up yet so we suggest

00:33:01.913 --> 00:33:04.949 align:start size:94% position:6%
you sign up for this
service, it's $15 a month

00:33:04.949 --> 00:33:06.317
or $20 a month.

00:33:06.317 --> 00:33:09.554 align:start size:88% position:13%
So they made millions
and millions of dollars.

00:33:09.554 --> 00:33:13.358
I thought that was very
unethical on their part

00:33:14.792 --> 00:33:18.363 align:start size:97% position:3%
and basically took advantage
of people and their fear.

00:33:18.363 --> 00:33:21.566
One thing is that when
you breach a company,

00:33:21.566 --> 00:33:25.603
if it's a retail environment
such as Home Depot or Target,

00:33:25.603 --> 00:33:27.105
and you're stealing
credit card numbers

00:33:27.105 --> 00:33:28.840 align:start size:94% position:6%
and debit card numbers you
have to get rid of that

00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:31.542
right away, it has a
very short shelf life.

00:33:31.542 --> 00:33:34.579
When you breach someone like
an Equifax you're stealing data

00:33:34.579 --> 00:33:38.116 align:start size:97% position:3%
that is name, social security
number, date of birth.

00:33:38.116 --> 00:33:39.517
You can't change your name,

00:33:39.517 --> 00:33:41.219
you can't change your
social security number,

00:33:41.219 --> 00:33:43.087
and you can't change
your date of birth.

00:33:43.087 --> 00:33:45.423
So the longer I hold that data

00:33:45.423 --> 00:33:47.859 align:start size:97% position:3%
the more valuable it becomes
when I go to sell it.

00:33:47.859 --> 00:33:50.261 align:start size:88% position:13%
So in those types of
breaches we usually find

00:33:50.261 --> 00:33:52.363
about a four-year lag

00:33:52.363 --> 00:33:54.832 align:start size:84% position:16%
because they warehouse
that information.

00:33:54.832 --> 00:33:57.468 align:start size:88% position:13%
So in reality we
haven't even been to see

00:33:57.468 --> 00:33:59.404 align:start size:84% position:16%
what's going to
happen with Equifax

00:33:59.404 --> 00:34:02.640
and the information that
was stolen off of Equifax.

00:34:02.640 --> 00:34:05.143
We're just now seeing the
South Carolina breach,

00:34:05.143 --> 00:34:07.612 align:start size:84% position:16%
the Target breach,
the Home Depot breach.

00:34:07.612 --> 00:34:10.214 align:start size:88% position:13%
When it came to personal
data such as name,

00:34:10.214 --> 00:34:12.216 align:start size:84% position:16%
social security
number, date of birth,

00:34:12.216 --> 00:34:13.885 align:start size:84% position:16%
because they can hold
that for so long.

00:34:13.885 --> 00:34:16.754
So we don't really know
the damage of Equifax.

00:34:16.754 --> 00:34:18.322
Now, here's the thing.

00:34:19.524 --> 00:34:21.025
What's really bad
about all of this

00:34:21.025 --> 00:34:24.295 align:start size:94% position:6%
is whether it be Equifax,
Experian, TransUnion,

00:34:24.295 --> 00:34:26.597
you never gave the credit bureau

00:34:26.597 --> 00:34:27.765
permission to have
your information.

00:34:27.765 --> 00:34:29.300 align:start size:84% position:16%
There's not one single
thing you signed

00:34:29.300 --> 00:34:32.170 align:start size:84% position:16%
that said hey, you
can store all my data,

00:34:32.170 --> 00:34:34.305
and you can make
billions of dollars

00:34:34.305 --> 00:34:37.642 align:start size:97% position:3%
selling it to credit purposes,
background checks, etc.,

00:34:37.642 --> 00:34:41.179 align:start size:84% position:16%
insurance, etc.,
you never said that.

00:34:41.179 --> 00:34:45.083
So I think that you and every
citizen, including myself,

00:34:45.083 --> 00:34:47.652
should have the right
to freeze their credit.

00:34:47.652 --> 00:34:50.822
And we should be able to say
no, you can't use my credit

00:34:50.822 --> 00:34:52.990
unless I give you permission

00:34:52.990 --> 00:34:56.094 align:start size:88% position:13%
to give that
information to someone.

00:34:56.094 --> 00:34:59.664 align:start size:84% position:16%
So up until this year
only eight states

00:34:59.664 --> 00:35:01.599 align:start size:81% position:19%
allowed you to
freeze your credit

00:35:01.599 --> 00:35:03.401
without charging you a fee.

00:35:03.401 --> 00:35:05.970 align:start size:84% position:16%
All the other states
required a fee,

00:35:05.970 --> 00:35:10.241
could be $10 to freeze
it, $15 to unfreeze it,

00:35:10.241 --> 00:35:12.510
$10 to freeze it back again.

00:35:12.510 --> 00:35:14.846 align:start size:84% position:16%
So not only was it
costly but for seniors

00:35:14.846 --> 00:35:18.249 align:start size:94% position:6%
it became very troublesome
and very involved

00:35:18.249 --> 00:35:20.218
in trying to keep up on
whether they froze it,

00:35:20.218 --> 00:35:21.619
they didn't freeze it.

00:35:21.619 --> 00:35:23.921 align:start size:94% position:6%
So for two years I
testified before Congress

00:35:23.921 --> 00:35:26.324
asking the government,
the federal government,

00:35:26.324 --> 00:35:29.327 align:start size:84% position:16%
to actually take it
and make it continuous

00:35:29.327 --> 00:35:31.329
throughout all the 50 states,

00:35:31.329 --> 00:35:33.764
so we had continuity.

00:35:33.764 --> 00:35:35.900
And that no credit bureau
in any of the 50 states

00:35:35.900 --> 00:35:37.635
could charge you to
freeze your credit,

00:35:37.635 --> 00:35:40.471 align:start size:94% position:6%
unfreeze your credit,
freeze your credit again.

00:35:40.471 --> 00:35:43.741 align:start size:94% position:6%
I'm happy to say that
Congress created the bill,

00:35:43.741 --> 00:35:46.744
they passed the bill, the
President signed the bill,

00:35:46.744 --> 00:35:50.281
and on September 1st of
this year, all 50 states,

00:35:50.281 --> 00:35:53.284
citizens will be able
to freeze their credit

00:35:53.284 --> 00:35:55.987
and then unfreeze it
and freeze it again

00:35:55.987 --> 00:35:58.356
at no cost to do so.

00:35:58.356 --> 00:36:02.760
And so if you were a senior
and you're 78 years old,

00:36:02.760 --> 00:36:04.862
you own your house,
you own your cars,

00:36:04.862 --> 00:36:07.298
you have credit cards, you're
not looking for any credit.

00:36:07.298 --> 00:36:08.766
You need to freeze your credit,

00:36:08.766 --> 00:36:10.968
there's no reason for
you to have your credit

00:36:10.968 --> 00:36:12.403
floating out there.

00:36:12.403 --> 00:36:14.739 align:start size:97% position:3%
If I'm a young man or
woman, I'm in the military,

00:36:14.739 --> 00:36:18.276
I'm getting sent overseas for
two years, to Afghanistan.

00:36:18.276 --> 00:36:21.179
I freeze my credit, I have
no reason to use my credit

00:36:21.179 --> 00:36:23.848 align:start size:88% position:13%
while I'm overseas
thousands of miles away.

00:36:23.848 --> 00:36:26.250 align:start size:88% position:13%
So freezing your credit
is the best option.

00:36:26.250 --> 00:36:27.885
And now you'll be
able to do that.

00:36:27.885 --> 00:36:31.389
And if you were 78
and you wanted to buy
a washer and dryer,

00:36:31.389 --> 00:36:33.457
but you wanted to finance it

00:36:33.457 --> 00:36:34.392 align:start size:81% position:19%
from the local
appliance company,

00:36:34.392 --> 00:36:35.860
then you go down and simply say

00:36:35.860 --> 00:36:38.796
I'm going to unfreeze my
credit to ABC Appliance,

00:36:38.796 --> 00:36:41.666
so they can give me this
washer and dryer on credit.

00:36:41.666 --> 00:36:44.669 align:start position:0%
And then freeze it back, they're
the only ones can see it.

00:36:44.669 --> 00:36:47.471 align:start position:0%
And that's an ability we
didn't have before we have now.

00:36:47.471 --> 00:36:50.041
- [Doug] So this would
be a much simpler process

00:36:50.041 --> 00:36:51.008
than it currently--

00:36:52.043 --> 00:36:53.044
- Than it currently is.

00:36:53.044 --> 00:36:54.545
And no cost involved.

00:36:54.545 --> 00:36:58.115
- [Doug] You mentioned, you
suggested the commoditization

00:36:58.115 --> 00:37:01.185
of this information, this
kind of dark Internet world

00:37:01.185 --> 00:37:05.022 align:start size:97% position:3%
that's out there were personal
data is literally sold

00:37:05.022 --> 00:37:08.292 align:start size:84% position:16%
to other people
for nefarious uses.

00:37:08.292 --> 00:37:11.128
And that it might be
years down the road

00:37:11.128 --> 00:37:15.233
before my information
makes me vulnerable.

00:37:16.567 --> 00:37:17.435
That's scary.

00:37:18.402 --> 00:37:19.804
- It is very scary.

00:37:19.804 --> 00:37:21.305
And you know this is not new,

00:37:21.305 --> 00:37:23.241 align:start size:94% position:6%
years ago it used to be
what we called chat rooms,

00:37:23.241 --> 00:37:24.976
where we'd monitor
these chat rooms

00:37:24.976 --> 00:37:27.278 align:start size:97% position:3%
and we see them selling
all these driver's license,

00:37:27.278 --> 00:37:28.980 align:start size:84% position:16%
mother's maiden
names, dates of birth,

00:37:28.980 --> 00:37:31.015
bank account information.

00:37:32.416 --> 00:37:33.884
Now you have the dark web where
they're doing the same thing

00:37:33.884 --> 00:37:36.687 align:start size:84% position:16%
but they're doing
it much bigger bulk.

00:37:36.687 --> 00:37:38.889 align:start size:94% position:6%
But yes, when you have
one of these big breaches,

00:37:38.889 --> 00:37:41.058
always keep in mind
that information,

00:37:41.058 --> 00:37:43.961
so when someone says to you
well what we're gonna do

00:37:43.961 --> 00:37:47.331
is offer you one-year credit
monitoring service for free,

00:37:47.331 --> 00:37:49.200
nothing's gonna
happen in a year.

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:51.269 align:start size:94% position:6%
First of all you've
already told the criminal,

00:37:51.269 --> 00:37:54.372 align:start position:0%
I've given all these people
credit monitoring for one year,

00:37:54.372 --> 00:37:57.608
so as a criminal I'm gonna
go OK, well then for one year

00:37:57.608 --> 00:37:59.343
I'm not gonna do anything.

00:37:59.343 --> 00:38:01.679 align:start size:97% position:3%
So one year of credit
monitoring would be worthless,

00:38:01.679 --> 00:38:03.848
you would always need at
least three or four years

00:38:03.848 --> 00:38:07.151 align:start size:97% position:3%
of credit monitoring to make
sure you're not picked up

00:38:07.151 --> 00:38:09.553
and victimized by it.

00:38:09.553 --> 00:38:11.922
- [Doug] Frank Abagnale
is an author, a lecturer,

00:38:11.922 --> 00:38:14.725
and a financial
fraud consultant.

00:38:14.725 --> 00:38:18.029 align:start position:0%
And your story, we started
talking about your life history,

00:38:18.029 --> 00:38:21.666
those formative five
years from 16 to 21

00:38:21.666 --> 00:38:25.236 align:start size:94% position:6%
that launched a career
helping people ultimately.

00:38:25.236 --> 00:38:27.905
But your story was
told in a movie.

00:38:27.905 --> 00:38:31.375 align:start size:88% position:13%
And a Broadway musical,
Catch Me if I Can.

00:38:31.375 --> 00:38:32.476
- Catch Me if You Can.

00:38:33.911 --> 00:38:36.280 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
- [Doug] What was
that experience like,

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:39.750 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
having your story told
in a different way.

00:38:39.750 --> 00:38:41.018 align:start size:88% position:13%
- You know I didn't
have I didn't have a lot

00:38:42.420 --> 00:38:43.754
to do with the movie, but
I thought it was great

00:38:43.754 --> 00:38:45.589
that it was Steven
Spielberg who did it.

00:38:45.589 --> 00:38:50.594
He loved the story because
of how the story ended out,

00:38:51.462 --> 00:38:52.763
and how my life turned out.

00:38:52.763 --> 00:38:56.167 align:start size:84% position:16%
So he held the
rights for 20 years,

00:38:56.167 --> 00:38:58.803 align:start size:94% position:6%
back when he was making
Jaws he bought the rights.

00:38:58.803 --> 00:39:01.038 align:start size:88% position:13%
So Barbara Walters asked
him in an interview,

00:39:01.038 --> 00:39:03.140 align:start size:94% position:6%
why did you wait 20
years to make this movie?

00:39:03.140 --> 00:39:04.809
And he said well,
I waited to see

00:39:04.809 --> 00:39:06.844 align:start size:94% position:6%
what the real Frank
Abagnale did with his life

00:39:06.844 --> 00:39:09.580 align:start size:84% position:16%
before I immortalized
him on film.

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:13.184 align:start size:97% position:3%
So I think it was, he loved
that part of the story,

00:39:13.184 --> 00:39:15.152
and he wanted the
world to know it.

00:39:15.152 --> 00:39:18.356
So I was very fortunate that
it was he who made the movie.

00:39:18.356 --> 00:39:20.658
I thought he did a great
job of telling the story.

00:39:20.658 --> 00:39:23.627
Broadway did a great job of
telling the story to music.

00:39:24.762 --> 00:39:26.831
I was very fortunate,
Leonardo DiCaprio,

00:39:26.831 --> 00:39:29.500
who did an amazing
job, he took the role

00:39:29.500 --> 00:39:31.769
when he was 27, 28 years old,

00:39:31.769 --> 00:39:34.004
and portrayed the part
of a 16 year old boy.

00:39:34.004 --> 00:39:36.574
Did an amazing, he's a
great character actor.

00:39:36.574 --> 00:39:39.977
Had people like Tom Hanks
and Christopher Walken,

00:39:39.977 --> 00:39:41.312
so they had an amazing cast.

00:39:41.312 --> 00:39:44.548
But I thought they
did a great job.

00:39:44.548 --> 00:39:46.217
So if you're gonna have
to have your story told,

00:39:46.217 --> 00:39:48.986
I was very fortunate it was he
who told the world the story.

00:39:48.986 --> 00:39:51.355 line:0%
- How has Catch Me if
You Can, the movie,

00:39:52.289 --> 00:39:53.257 line:0%
affected your life?

00:39:54.125 --> 00:39:55.359
- I get asked quite often,

00:39:55.359 --> 00:39:56.927
how did the movie
change my life.

00:39:56.927 --> 00:39:59.597
And the truth is I do
the same thing today

00:39:59.597 --> 00:40:01.665
that I did years ago.

00:40:01.665 --> 00:40:05.002 align:start size:97% position:3%
The only difference is I
get paid more money to do it

00:40:05.002 --> 00:40:07.605
and people want to take
their picture with me.

00:40:07.605 --> 00:40:09.540
I don't know how many
thousands of pictures

00:40:09.540 --> 00:40:11.308
I've taken with people.

00:40:11.308 --> 00:40:13.277 align:start size:84% position:16%
You know I had
written five books,

00:40:13.277 --> 00:40:17.381
I had been on the lecture
series for years and years.

00:40:17.381 --> 00:40:19.917
No one ever asked to
have a photo with me.

00:40:19.917 --> 00:40:23.187 align:start size:94% position:6%
Now everywhere I go, in
the airport wherever I am,

00:40:23.187 --> 00:40:24.955
someone wants take
a picture with me.

00:40:24.955 --> 00:40:27.858
So I think that has a lot to
do what people have cameras,

00:40:27.858 --> 00:40:30.494
and social media, they want
to put it up on social media.

00:40:30.494 --> 00:40:34.298 align:start size:84% position:16%
So I always say, my
sons always remind me,

00:40:34.298 --> 00:40:35.933
you know Dad you tell people
